%T A338444 62,66,33,35,70,74,37,39,78,82,41,43,86,94,47,51,102,106,53,55,110,
%U A338444 114,57,59,118,122,61,65,130,134,67,69,138,142,71,73,146,154,77
%N A338444 Lexicographically earliest sequence of distinct squarefree numbers such that for any prime p, any run of consecutive multiples of p has length exactly 2.
%C A338444 This sequence is a squarefree variant of A280864.
%C A338444 Conjecture: this sequence is a permutation of the squarefree numbers (A005117).
%C A338444 From _Michael De Vlieger_, Jun 19 2026: (Start)
%C A338444 a(n) is even for n congruent to 2 or 3 (mod 4), else a(n) is odd.
%C A338444 Consequently, for m > 0, the following are true:
%C A338444   1.) a(4*m+2) = 2*a(4*m+1).
%C A338444   2.) a(4*m+3) = 2*a(4*m+4).
%C A338444   3.) a(4*m) and a(4*m+1) are coprime.
%C A338444   4.) (a(4*m+3)-a(4*m+2))/4 = (a(4*m+4)-a(4*m+1))/2 != 0.
%C A338444   5.) a(4*m+i), with m > 0 and i in {2, 3} are composite (in A120944).
%C A338444   6.) a(4*m+i), with i in {0, 1} are sometimes prime.
%C A338444 The number m = 2037 is the smallest such that (a(4*m+3)-a(4*m+2))/4 = (a(4*m+4)-a(4*m+1))/2 is negative; a(8150) = 20098 = 2*13*773, a(8151) = 20094 = 2*13*17*197.  (End)
%H A338444 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A338444/b338444.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A338444 Rémy Sigrist, <a href="/A338444/a338444.txt">C program for A338444</a>
